Jan,

Thanks for being willing to say something controversial.  Let me be sure 
I&#39;m understanding you.  Are you saying one of these two things, or a 
third thing entirely?

1) Teams need only test that the whole system meets client requirements, 
not the behavior of any individual class.
2) Teams need only write all of their tests during a first-pass 
&quot;requirements&quot; phase, and not during development.

Thanks,

    David

j_cumps wrote:
&gt; &lt;controversial&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m still not convinced of the economics of unit testing at the 
&gt; lowest level.
&gt; I&#39;ve been lurking this list for quite some time, attended online and 
&gt; offline seminars, listened to to Agile, XP and TDD talks, ...
&gt;
&gt; And apply it at work.
&gt;
&gt; I am convinced that TDD is a right approach.
&gt; I see big value in the agile methods.
&gt; But to my feeling unit testing can be done at the requirements level.
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s why I am thinking about testdriving this approach:
&gt;
&gt; 1: Write unit tests only to test the requirements.
&gt; 2: Write the code that implements these requirements, until tests 
&gt; pass.
&gt; 3: Run the unit tests together with a code coverage tool
&gt; 4: delete all executable lines of code not covered by the unit test
&gt;
&gt; &lt;/controversial&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Regards, Jan
